Name: jumpListCategory

Type: property

Syntax: set the jumpListCategory of <stack> to <categoryName>

Summary:
Sets the section heading for tasks in the Windows taskbar Jump List.

Associations: stack

Introduced: 1.0.0

OS: windows

Platforms: desktop

Example:
-- Use a custom section heading
set the jumpListCategory of this stack to "Actions"
set the jumpListTasks of this stack to "New Card|newCard,Open Stack...|openStack"

Example:
-- Revert to the standard Tasks section
set the jumpListCategory of this stack to empty
set the jumpListTasks of this stack to "New Card|newCard"

Parameters:
stack:
A reference to a stack, or an expression that evaluates to a stack.

categoryName:
The heading text shown above the task items in the Jump List.
Pass empty to use the standard pinned "Tasks" section instead.

Value:
The <jumpListCategory> of a stack returns the string most recently set.
The default value is empty.

Description:
Use the <jumpListCategory> property to control where and how task items
defined by <jumpListTasks> appear in the Windows taskbar Jump List.

When <jumpListCategory> is empty (the default), tasks are placed in the
standard "Tasks" section, which Windows always pins at the bottom of
the Jump List below any Recent or Frequent items.

When <jumpListCategory> is set to a non-empty string, tasks are placed
in a custom named section using that string as the heading. Custom
sections appear above the Recent/Frequent sections and above the
standard Tasks section.

Changing <jumpListCategory> takes effect immediately and re-applies the
current <jumpListTasks> list under the new heading.

>*Note:* The <jumpListCategory> property only has a visual effect on
> Windows. On macOS and Linux the property is accepted without error
> but has no effect.

>*Note:* The <jumpListCategory> property is not persistent — it is not
> saved into the stack file. Set it alongside <jumpListTasks> in a
> `preOpenStack` or `startUp` handler.

References: jumpListTasks (property), taskbarProgress (property)

Tags: windowing
